        "text": "**Exploring script implementation**\n\nIt seems like the user mentioned that glob with brace might be unsupported. I need to focus on implementing scripts directly in .github. I’m thinking about creating a validator that reads JSON and inspects command edits, using a PreToolUse event type. The user brought up something about a pre-commit hook, but it’s essential to clarify that the current hook probably triggers before any commit-related tool usage. I’m considering how to set up the validation script accordingly without actually running shell commands during the assessment. **Examining script patterns**\n\nI need to follow the guardrail scripts in implementing my new script. It’ll read JSON from stdin with tool_name and tool_input. I’m considering whether to only validate if tool_name indicates a commit tool, but that might not be available here. So maybe I could just check the hook payload—if it's not related to file-editing or commit tools, I’d exit. The user mentioned pre-commit guardrails, but the existing pre-commit hook doesn’t inspect stdin; it just runs the script. My new script will likely need to combine these elements effectively! **Analyzing the PreToolUse hook**\n\nI’m considering the PreToolUse hook and whether it allows nonzero code blocks for tool use. It seems like I can combine various elements, ensuring not to use shell commands since I can’t run tests. I should rely on reasoning and reviewing instead. I’m contemplating if I need to inspect the expected patterns in the output. Also, I’ve got to figure out the specifics of the barrel-file convention, which involves importing from barrel files (like index.ts) rather than using internal module paths. **Evaluating path conventions**\n\nI’m thinking about relative paths that have at least one parent or sibling segment and more than one segment after normalization. It seems paths like \"../../src/rules/business-rules.js\" would be suspect. Allowed paths would be ones that have a simpler